      "text": "Hạnd·schuh\nmasculine noun\nglove"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf4ec4fff8607331",
      "text": "[…], why the current crisis is all about thinking about technology. If this crisis is about a shift from subject to project, as this book tries to show, then it is about a crisis of technology. If technology used to mean \"to exist\" in the sense of \"to confront,\" then a change is currently taking place in which technology turns itself inside out like a glove and \"to exist\" now takes on the sense of \"to design. To \"design technology\" would thus mean to design oneself out of subservience into design, out of the self into the open field of possibilities. Such a radical and self-biting formulation of the question of technology demands to be made plausible."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "74676796714521a3",
      "text": "Vilém Flusser, [[Vom Subjekt zum Projekt]]: Menschwerdung. 1994, Schriften / Vilém Flusser, 3 (Bensheim und Düsseldorf: Bollmann, 1994), p. 136."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f8c9180dee3dc0be",
      "text": "However, all this is only valid if we recognize the [[Negation]] of an object on the part of a subject in the striking of a stone. But the facts can also be seen differently, it can be turned upside down like a glove, as said above. Then one no longer sees the hominid with its toothache and the stone in its materiality, but the stone beating. Only then one sees the technique. And other questions arise. For example: When hitting a hominid comes out on the one hand and on the other hand a hewn stone, but what was before? By no means a non-hewing hominid, because a hominid is after all a cattle that hews stones, and by no means an unhewn stone, because a stone is after all an object for hominids."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cef9f99bec4a2bad",
      "text": "The following answer is more likely: Before there was a possibility to hit stones, and from this possibility on the one hand stones and on the other hand hominids have been concretized. - Another example: After the stone-hammering, the hominid, which emerged from it, uses the resulting stone like an artificial fang: Did natural teeth, which were simulated in the stone, exist before with any mammals? The question is to be answered in the negative, because only in the stone it turned out what \"tooth\" is. In the opposite part the hominid comes only on the fact that he has teeth, after he has produced the stone, and these teeth are possible pointed stones, which concretize themselves only in the stone-beating. And if the hominid says afterwards of cave tigers that they have teeth, then he means peculiar pointed stones. In short, if one looks at the matter in this way, then the whole objective world appears as a projection from the concrete stone-beating – as designed by the hominid – and the hominid for his part as a projection on the side opposite to the matter."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "439bd956adacff2c",
      "text": "This is what it looks like when we try to get back to the matter at hand from the millennia of talk about the matter - when we try to let the phenomenon of \"hitting a stone\" have its say. The situation that arises is extraordinarily uncomfortable; for the answers to the questions of a different kind are not, after all, real answers, but invitations to ask further. As soon as one turns the matter over like a glove, a wide field of questions opens up to be asked, and neither answers nor even a horizon for these questions can be foreseen. Into this opening, however, the question of designing technology as a conversion of the subject out of itself is to be posed."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5d9815e49989b126",
      "text": "As soon as one turns the matter of technology over like a glove (as soon as one sets oneself up as a project), it becomes clear that it can no longer be a matter of exploiting objects and objectifying values. In other words, technology is then no longer \"work\" (but about that later). On the contrary, it must now be a matter of concretizing the ought out of possibilities. For in such an attitude there are no objects that could be exploited: Everything that was previously regarded as an object (such as teeth and stones) is now seen through as a projection, as a consequence of preceding technique. Technique is now about picking out of the possible that which is supposed to be. The final goal of a technical gesture is then to make the should (the model) emerge from the field of possibilities in such a way that it looks like an object. These pseudo-objects produced by technology are no longer objects negated by a subject, but projections designed from a project. They are not objectified values, but nothing but \"values\", which are however concentrated in such a way that they look like objects: \"pure\" intentions, and this is what is meant by the word \"immaterial culture\". An example can bring this to mind:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "28e9b123ed940c43",
      "text": "From the universe of numbers, understood as a field of [[Possibilities]], some algorithms are picked out because they \"should be\". These algorithms are processed, fed into a [[Holograph]] and from there designed into space in the form of a four-dimensional cube. The particles \"corresponding\" to the chosen numbers are scattered so densely [⇒ [[‘Dense’ Address]]] that the cube now stands in space like an object. Such a cube would be \"immaterial\", \"pure\" intention, \"pure\" ought, it is not an object which could be [[negate]]d by a subject [⇒ [[Negation]]]. With it there can no longer be talk of \"being\", but only of \"ought\", and a new [[Ontology]] is to be brought into play here. Even to call this cube a \"simulation\" of an object makes little sense. (p. 144)"
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "4edc456a6904a9b5",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "reference",
      "id": "664d0021da035e3b",
      "site": "wiki.ralfbarkow.ch",
      "slug": "hologram-of-a-table",
      "title": "Hologram of a Table",
      "text": "A densely enough scattered [[Hologram]] of a table, for example, would be, if it succeeded, indistinguishable from a \"perceived given\" table. (Flusser, [[Vom Subjekt zum Projekt]], 122–123)"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2efd48792ee82fba",
      "text": "The example shows what is meant by \"designing technology\". What existence will emerge from this technology is not yet foreseeable, because there is no subject (no \"author\") in this technology, but only a networked projecting, so that the word \"existence\" gains a meaning, which we only begin to suspect. We will \"be there\" differently."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "79ce36c2fb74e0f9",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f4f4158e85bc35cb",
      "text": "They are surprised that they are paid for something they would do anyway. At second glance, however, the denial proves to be extremely difficult. The point is to propose a new concept of freedom (new political categories). In order to understand that work makes one unfree, one must know what is meant by \"freedom\". The ancients seem to have known it: Contemplation is freedom, such as theory and Sabbath (which in Christianity was summarized in the term \"prayer\"). This can no longer be true. We can no longer dismiss the work as a negation of contemplation (as a-scholie, as neg-otium), i.e., suggest, for example, academies, Sabbath consecrations, or monasteries as an alternative to K Z 's. We have to look for alternatives to K Z 's in technology, that is, to try to peel the concept of freedom out of technology. The K Z is itself a consequence of the technique. So we must try to analyze technology for the possibilities for unfreedom and freedom hidden in it: to examine technology, turned inside out like a glove, for possible developments of work and freedom. (p. 149)"
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "6f78c73dd3c7ea15",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "43e06e3940d2f6a8",
      "text": "The picture we are in does not have a two-dimensional base like an Escher drawing, but it can be compared with a [[Hologram]]. If a hologram is to bend, it must reach into another dimension than the usual third. Since the outstretched, not yet fully human hand can reach for itself, for that not yet fully human hand which is searching for the fully human, it must be able to turn around itself, to bend comparable to a Möbius strip. If we want to remain in the picture, then we must bend ourselves (and the picture in which we are) à la Möbius."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c8b2ad0b9b71c029",
      "text": "This sounds dizzying when you hear it, but even less so when you try to visualize it. Then one finds out that with the word \"Überlegung\" nothing else is meant. \"Reflecting\", radically carried out, can mean nothing else than folding the course of thoughts into a Möbius strip. And the Möbius dizziness is experienced by everyone who tries to think about something (whatever) radically. Maybe this is connected with the fact that we think with two hands, back and forth between the right and the left one. But the two hands can only be brought to coincide with each other in the fourth dimension, by a möbius-like rotation. Much easily this is the explanation for the fact that one has the impression to turn over gloves when doing philosophy. Not the notorious mirror, but the upturned glove is the tool of reflection. (p. 201)"
    }
