        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "f4f4158e85bc35cb",
        "text": "They are surprised that they are paid for something they would do anyway. At second glance, however, the denial proves to be extremely difficult. The point is to propose a new concept of freedom (new political categories). In order to understand that work makes one unfree, one must know what is meant by \"freedom\". The ancients seem to have known it: Contemplation is freedom, such as theory and Sabbath (which in Christianity was summarized in the term \"prayer\"). This can no longer be true. We can no longer dismiss the work as a negation of contemplation (as a-scholie, as neg-otium), i.e., suggest, for example, academies, Sabbath consecrations, or monasteries as an alternative to K Z 's. We have to look for alternatives to K Z 's in technology, that is, to try to peel the concept of freedom out of technology. The K Z is itself a consequence of the technique. So we must try to analyze technology for the possibilities for unfreedom and freedom hidden in it: to examine technology, turned inside out like a glove, for possible developments of work and freedom."
